TIPS!! Coconut flour Flatbread! 
So tasty and easy to make! âœ¨
I love healthy eating but I also love cooking easy and delicious recipes! This is exactly that! You donâ€™t need any mixer, just mix all the ingredients with a table spoon and your flatbread will be ready, in only 25minğŸ¤©
I was extremely bloated all last week. Then I made this delicious flatbread with a Psyllium Husk (twice) and my stomach has returned to normal again! Psyllium Husk does wonders!! Psyllium is a form of fiber made from the husks of the Plantago ovata plantâ€™s seeds. It helps promote regularity and overall digestive health. I highly recommending it ğŸ˜‰ if you feel bloated or constipated ğŸ™ƒ
Here are the ingredients and the instructions if youâ€™re willing to try them ;) Ingredients:
1/2 cup Coconut flour
2 tablespoons Psyllium Husk powder
1/4 cup Coconut oil (or melted butter)
1/2 teaspoon Salt
1 teaspoon Baking powder
1 Cup Boiling water
Herbs/garlic powder to flavour optional

Instructions:
Mix the dry ingredients with a hand whisk.
Add the oil and blend well. It will look like a nut butter.
Add the boiling water, half at a time and blend until a dough like mixture forms.
Divide the mixture into 6 balls.
Roll the balls between 2 sheets of parchment paper and flatten out.
Either use them flattened or cut them into a circle with a saucepan lid.
Dry fry in a pan for 2â€“ 3 minutes each side, until golden.

Today Boise Celebrates the 30th annual pride festival! It all started 1 year after I was born, and I must say, our teenagers live in a world far different than the one I grew up in, and I now understand the work of generations before me. Today I get to do something that was unthinkable 20 years ago. Today I get to be visible as not only a gay man, but as an LGBT face in the Boise-based Albertsons grocer family. I stand with my local store level colleagues with excitement that we can be who we are in all aspects of our life. As a corporate level employee of Albertsons Companies, I also stand on behalf of my nationwide peers who work under our various banner names in areas that aren't as loving and accepting as our Boise, ID. Whether you show it in public, or see it in the mirror, I pray that everyone finds pride in who they are, and always chooses love and acceptance over hate and judgement. Happy 30th Pride Day, Boise!

Shadowland by Peter Straub is the coming of age story of Tom and Del who meet at a prestigious boarding school.
.
The structure of the book splits it into two main parts. The first being the time spent at the boarding school and the events which take place there setting up the creepy and eerie vision of what Shadowland is about and then there is the second part set at Coleman Collins home. A house made of secret doorways and traps which lure the boys to learn about real magic and whatâ€™s really happing in Shadowland.
.
Initially I thought this would be a horror novel but the further I read the more it was obvious its a fantasy one with horror elements. Itâ€™s been said that you could compare it slightly to Stephen Kingâ€™s IT and on some level I suppose you could as the similar factor of Shadowland being of magic, the beings that dwell there, give off that familiar feeling. This book was written in 1980, where the idea of young magicians finding each other to then go on to defeat a sorcerer was fairly new.
.
The imagery was quite gruesome and shocking on a few occasions. There is a specific badger scene which had me quite surprised, some of the scenes that take place in Shadowland felt like you were on some kind of a trip. Those elements were well written. The first part of the book gave a good build up however it felt like it lagged on more than one occasion. Thereâ€™s no doubt that the fantasy themes are heavily present throughout, I wouldnâ€™t go as far as saying it was terrifying, this could also be because Iâ€™ve read it as an adult, had I read it in my teens maybe I would have felt differently.
.
The book has received some harsh criticism over not being as iconic as Ghost Story (which iâ€™ve yet to read), I wouldnâ€™t say its a bad novel at all, it was a good read, and if I had to score it out of 5 I would give it a 3.75.
.

#christmasbreak 2000, I took a one month #leaveofabsence from #work because mom was ill. I had been banking with #citibank since I first arrived in #manhattan . My #landlady who suggested me to open up a #bankaccount .

There was no problem. They only asked a minimum of $100 to open up an account. 
I returned home permanently the end of 2001. In January 2002, Citibank called and said there had been a change of #policy , unless I could increase my #savingsaccount to the new minimum balance of $5000, they had no choice but closing my account by the end of the month. 
I didn't know  there were so many rich people in the beloved country of mine who could maintain minimum of 5 grand, considering the #exchangerate was quite high. (and still is) Rp.15000, = $1 only approximately. 
So I withdrew the #money and went to #localbank .

They asked for Rp.500,000 surely I could do that. However, my #identitycard was just a bit , I repeat slightly ruined by watermark that affected the end of my #signature marking although it was still very visible.

The super 'nice' #customerservice in front of me said sorry my #application is denied. I said to her, look.everything matches with the #passport yes? With signature intact and all the rest of the information matched.  Dob , name etc.

She said no. Sorry

Oh. Alright then. Bye.thanks for your #senseandsensibility

My mom was using that bank for as long as I could remember. After father passed away, she asked me to put my name in her account as join account (?) in case something happened.

When I got a #check from overseas, I couldn't #cash it.

I could no longer remember what were their excuses, but I closed the #account right away because what is the function of #banking #system if their clients couldn't cash in a check????? Do tell. Because I am confused. Are you ?

Sometimes I see simple scenes like this and I realise that I'm often so caught up with my fixed schedule and my tightly-packed life that I forget that there is beauty in taking some time to relax. I forget that there is a world outside of huddling around my laptop as I eat a quick supper, and that there are places for me find a change of pace if only I would bother to open my eyes. This past week has been hard on me in that I've had more anxieties to deal with and made more mistakes than I would've liked. Still, there have been a few beautiful drops of sunshine dispersed throughout that've made the week that little bit easier to bear. Hopefully, this coming week and the rest of the quarter will be more about me finding a balance in my life and doing better in everything I'm a part of. To everyone else who is having a hard time, I wish you all the best, and may you always find time to appreciate the little moments when you get the chance to witness the grand beauty of life. #SunsetRec #UCLA #MassOnTheGrass #JustSundayThings #randomthoughts #lifeisbeautiful
